{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14587"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.54,0.29,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7280"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42614"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1594"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43543"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for routine review. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, hypertension, osteoarthritis, and known colonic angiodysplasia. His medications include metformin, perindopril, and paracetamol. He had previously undergone several endoscopic procedures for the angiodysplasia, but has elected for less invasive management from this point onwards.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe reports increasing fatigue and shortness of breath on exertion for the past three months. He has previously tried oral iron supplements but experienced significant gastrointestinal side effects. On examination, he appears pale but not in distress. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 138/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Heart and lung examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecent blood tests show: Haemoglobin 85 g/L (130-170), Mean cell volume 75 fL (80-100), Serum ferritin 15 \u00b5g/L (30-300), Transferrin saturation 10% (20-55).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence oral iron supplementation","Regular iron infusions","Single dose iron infusion","Blood transfusion","Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic iron deficiency anaemia with low haemoglobin, ferritin, and transferrin saturation. The microcytic anaemia (low MCV) is consistent with iron deficiency. Given his known colonic angiodysplasia, which causes chronic gastrointestinal blood loss, and previous intolerance to oral iron, parenteral iron replacement is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular iron infusions\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate management strategy. This approach allows for consistent iron replacement to compensate for ongoing losses from angiodysplasia. Regular monitoring of response is particularly important in patients with chronic blood loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the patient has previously experienced significant side effects. Additionally, with ongoing blood loss from angiodysplasia, oral iron alone may be insufficient to maintain adequate iron stores.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose iron infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate given the chronic nature of blood loss from angiodysplasia. Regular infusions allow for better maintenance of iron stores and monitoring of response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate unless there was acute symptomatic anaemia or cardiovascular compromise. It does not address the underlying chronic iron deficiency and carries unnecessary risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythropoiesis-stimulating agents\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in iron deficiency anaemia without chronic kidney disease or chemotherapy-induced anaemia. The primary issue is iron deficiency due to chronic blood loss which needs to be corrected with iron replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of angiodysplasia explains the chronic nature of the iron deficiency and supports the need for ongoing iron replacement rather than a single intervention. Regular monitoring of haemoglobin, ferritin, and transferrin saturation will guide the frequency of iron infusions needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iron deficiency in elderly patients requires investigation for underlying causes, particularly gastrointestinal blood loss.","Regular iron infusions may be appropriate when oral iron is ineffective or poorly tolerated.","Angiodysplasia is a common cause of chronic gastrointestinal blood loss in elderly patients."],"references":["Becq A, Sidhu R, Goltstein LC, Dray X. Recent advances in the treatment of refractory gastrointestinal angiodysplasia. United European Gastroenterology Journal. 2024 Sep 4. Available online at ; https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/ueg2.12648"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42614"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42614"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T19:42:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T19:45:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7280"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{